      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Dividing Fences and Boundary Issues When Selling a Brisbane Property: What Sellers Must Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Fences are visible at every open home and they are a frequent point of buyer concern. The Queensland framework that governs them is set by the Neighbourhood Disputes (Dividing Fences and Trees) Act 2011, and it shapes both the cost of repairs and the disclosure obligations on sellers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Dividing fences are one of the more common sources of friction between Brisbane neighbours. They are also a frequent question at open homes, particularly when the fence is leaning, rotting, or visibly different on either side. Sellers benefit from understanding the Queensland framework before listing, because it affects what they have to disclose, what they can expect a buyer's solicitor to ask, and what work is worth doing in advance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, the Neighbourhood Disputes (Dividing Fences and Trees) Act 2011 governs dividing fences. A dividing fence is a fence on or near the common boundary between two adjoining properties. Under the Act, dividing fences are typically a shared responsibility, with both owners contributing to construction and maintenance of a fence that meets a minimum standard. The Act sets out the formal process for resolving disagreements, the obligations on each party, and the dispute resolution path through the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal (QCAT).</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'sufficient dividing fence' means</h2>
      <p>The Act sets a minimum standard, called a 'sufficient dividing fence'. The standard is what is reasonably effective for the type of property. For most residential blocks in inner Brisbane, that means a timber paling fence of standard height (typically 1.8 metres) or an equivalent fence in another material such as Colorbond. For rural blocks the standard may be a post and wire fence, and for properties in heritage areas there may be specific local requirements.</p>

      <p>An owner can request a fence that exceeds the minimum standard (a higher fence, a more expensive material, ornamental features), but the requesting owner must pay the additional cost above what a sufficient dividing fence would have cost. The neighbour's contribution is capped at what the sufficient fence would have cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who pays for repair or replacement</h2>
      <p>Owners on both sides of a dividing fence typically share the cost of a sufficient dividing fence equally. This applies to construction, repair, and replacement. If one fence is damaged by a storm, vandalism, or accident caused by one of the owners, the owner responsible for the damage may have a higher share of the cost. Where the damage cause is unclear, the default split is equal.</p>

      <p>The formal process for cost-sharing is to issue a Notice to Contribute under the Act. The notice sets out the proposed work, the cost split, and the materials. The neighbour has one month to respond. If the neighbour agrees, the work proceeds and costs are split as agreed. If the neighbour disagrees or does not respond, the matter can be referred to QCAT for resolution. QCAT has the authority to order the work to proceed and to determine the cost split.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers must disclose</h2>
      <p>The standard Queensland sale contract includes provisions about boundary issues, and the seller's solicitor will advise on specific disclosures based on the property. Generally, sellers should disclose any current dispute about a fence (this is material to the buyer), any QCAT order in force regarding the fence, any voluntary agreement with the neighbour about future fencing or fence costs, and any retaining wall in disrepair that sits in or under the fence line.</p>

      <p>Retaining walls are often the unspoken cost behind a fence. A timber paling fence sitting on top of a retaining wall in disrepair is a much larger problem than the fence alone, because the retaining wall is the structural element supporting the property. Responsibility for retaining walls is more complex than fences and is not always shared equally. Disclosure of a known retaining wall issue is essential.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The boundary survey question</h2>
      <p>If there is doubt about where the boundary actually sits, an identification survey from a registered cadastral surveyor is the appropriate tool. Boundary issues that are discovered after sale can become a buyer's claim against the seller, particularly if the seller had reason to suspect there was a problem and did not investigate. Commissioning a survey before listing gives the seller control over the information and the opportunity to address any issue cleanly before going to market.</p>

      <p>A survey is not necessary for every sale. Where the boundaries are clearly marked, no neighbour has raised a concern, and no structures sit close to the line, the existing title plan is usually sufficient. Where any of those conditions does not hold, a survey is worth the cost (typically $1,500 to $3,000 in Brisbane).</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common Brisbane fence situations</h2>
      <p>Several patterns recur across inner Brisbane sales. Old timber fences leaning or rotting are by far the most common. Buyers expect this to be either resolved before settlement or factored into the price. A leaning fence at an open home is one of the items that produces a visible reaction from buyers and reduces the perceived condition of the property.</p>

      <p>Fences encroaching on the boundary by a small margin are also common, particularly on older lots where fences have been rebuilt over decades without a survey. A few centimetres of drift may have been tolerated for years but a fresh survey, often commissioned by the buyer, may identify the encroachment and trigger a negotiation.</p>

      <p>Trees overhanging or pushing fences are a third recurring pattern. The Trees provisions of the same 2011 Act apply, and the resolution path is similar to the dividing fence process: the affected owner can request the neighbour deal with the tree, and if not resolved, the matter can go to QCAT.</p>

      <p>Retaining walls in or under fences are the fourth pattern, and the most variable. Responsibility for retaining walls depends on who built the wall, who benefits from the wall, and what agreements (formal or informal) exist between the neighbours. A retaining wall in disrepair is materially different from a fence in disrepair and is worth obtaining specific legal advice on before listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dispute scenarios</h2>
      <p>The most common active disputes that surface at sale time are: a neighbour refusing to contribute to a fence repair the seller wants done before listing; a fence that was erected on the wrong side of the boundary by a previous owner or by the neighbour; a neighbour whose trees have damaged the fence; and missing boundary marker stones or pegs that make it impossible to determine where the boundary actually sits.</p>

      <p>Each of these has a resolution path, but each takes time. A Notice to Contribute gives the neighbour one month to respond. If the matter goes to QCAT, the timeline can extend to several months depending on the tribunal's caseload. Sellers who know there is a dispute should resolve it before listing where possible, or disclose it cleanly in the contract if resolution is not feasible within the campaign timeframe.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before listing</h2>
      <p>Walk the perimeter of the property and identify any fence or boundary issue. Note any leaning, rotting, or visibly damaged sections. Check the alignment of the fence with what you understand the boundary to be. Review any prior correspondence with neighbours about boundaries, fences, trees, or retaining walls.</p>

      <p>Address obvious fence repairs before listing. A tired fence is visible at every open home and reduces the perceived condition of the property. Replacement of a single damaged section is usually quick and inexpensive (a few hundred dollars), and the visual improvement at the open home is significant.</p>

      <p>If a dispute is active, attempt to resolve it before listing. Issue the Notice to Contribute, negotiate with the neighbour, or proceed to QCAT if necessary. Resolution before listing is preferable to disclosure mid-campaign, because the dispute will affect buyer confidence even when properly disclosed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure to the buyer</h2>
      <p>The standard Queensland sale contract includes clauses about boundary issues, and the buyer's solicitor will check the title for any encumbrances or covenants affecting boundaries. Disclosure of known disputes is essential, both to comply with the seller's obligations and to avoid post-settlement claims. A buyer who discovers an undisclosed material dispute may have grounds to terminate the contract or seek a price reduction.</p>

      <p>A clean disclosure is straightforward: identify the issue, describe the current state, attach any QCAT orders or written agreements, and let the buyer's solicitor advise the buyer on the implications. Most boundary and fence issues are manageable with full disclosure. The damage to the campaign comes from undisclosed issues that surface during the buyer's due diligence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Typical Brisbane fence repair costs</h2>
      <p>Realistic 2028 figures for budget purposes: a timber paling fence section repair runs $200 to $600 depending on length and access. Full replacement of a timber paling fence sits at $130 to $220 per linear metre installed, inclusive of materials and labour. Colorbond fencing runs $90 to $160 per linear metre installed. Removal of an old fence ahead of new installation is typically $30 to $60 per linear metre.</p>

      <p>These costs are typically shared with the neighbour for a sufficient dividing fence, so the seller's portion is approximately half of the total figures. Where the seller has requested an upgraded fence above the minimum standard, the seller pays the additional cost above the sufficient-fence baseline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework</h2>
      <p>Fences are visible, frequent points of buyer concern. Addressing them before listing prevents inspection-day questions and reduces the risk of mid-campaign negotiation. Active disputes must be disclosed. Boundary uncertainties should be resolved with a survey before contract where there is doubt. The cost of getting this right before listing is small compared to the cost of mid-contract disputes or post-settlement claims.</p>

